2. Dynamic Queries Using Specifications

Theory
Specifications allow you to build queries dynamically at runtime.
Useful when you don’t know all the query conditions in advance (e.g., search filters).
Spring Data JPA provides the JpaSpecificationExecutor interface for this.

1. Dynamic Queries Using Specifications
What are Specifications?
Specifications let you build queries in Java code, dynamically, based on conditions you know
only at runtime (like user search filters).
You don’t have to write fixed query methods for every possible combination of filters.

How do you use Specifications?
Step 1: Extend JpaSpecificationExecutor in your repository

Implementation
Step 1: Extend JpaSpecificationExecutor

public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long>, JpaSpecificationExecutor<User> {}

Step 2: Create Specifications

import org.springframework.data.jpa.domain.Specification;

Specification<User> ageGreaterThan(int age) {
    return (root, query, cb) -> cb.greaterThan(root.get("age"), age);
}

Specification<User> nameEquals(String name) {
    return (root, query, cb) -> cb.equal(root.get("name"), name);
}

Step 3: Combine Specifications

Specification<User> spec = ageGreaterThan(18).and(nameEquals("Alice"));
List<User> users = userRepository.findAll(spec);

You can combine specifications with .and(), .or(), etc.


Q. What Are root, query, and cb?

When you write a Specification in Spring Data JPA, you use a lambda expression that takes
three parameters:

(root, query, cb) -> ...
These correspond to:

(i) root (Root<T>)
Represents the entity/table you are querying.
Used to access fields/columns of your entity.
Example: root.get("age") accesses the age field of the User entity.

(ii) query (CriteriaQuery<?>)
Represents the overall query being built.
Used for advanced query features (like grouping, ordering, etc.).
For simple Specifications, you often don’t need to use it directly.

(iii) cb (CriteriaBuilder)
The CriteriaBuilder is a helper object that provides methods to build query conditions (predicates).
Example: cb.greaterThan(...), cb.equal(...), cb.and(...), etc.
Example Breakdown

Specification<User> ageGreaterThan(int age) {
    return (root, query, cb) -> cb.greaterThan(root.get("age"), age);
}

Info:
root.get("age"): Accesses the age field of the User entity.
cb.greaterThan(...): Builds a "greater than" condition for the query.

Ex 2:

Specification<User> nameEquals(String name) {
    return (root, query, cb) -> cb.equal(root.get("name"), name);
}

Info:
root.get("name"): Accesses the name field of the User entity.
cb.equal(...): Builds an "equals" condition for the query.


In Short:
root: The entity/table you’re querying (lets you access fields).
query: The query object (lets you customize the query, usually for advanced use).
cb: The CriteriaBuilder (lets you build conditions for your query).


